+# closing ray [0,1] coarsely to bracket the first tick-fraction at which the two boxes' engagement
+# surfaces meet (obb_front_reach_overlap true); BISECT then converges that bracket. The circular
+# reject in resolve_toi_and_commit already filters far-apart pairs, so only genuinely near-contact
+# pairs ever run this. Precision of the returned fraction: bracket width (1/SCAN)/2^BISECT ~=
+# (1/128)/2^50 ~= 7e-18 -- machine epsilon; the returned point is on the TRUE (just-overlapping) side,
+# so residual box overlap after commit is closing_rate * that width ~= 1e-17 lattice units (well under
+# any ep) yet obb_front_reach_overlap still fires there, so contact triggers (no stall). A touch
+# interval narrower than the SCAN step (1/128 in s) can be skipped -- only a near-tangential grazing
+# pass; the effect is contact deferred one tick (bodies re-evaluated next tick), never a rest-state
+# interpenetration.
+# [v2 Stage C perf reconcile, ED-MB-0011] Scan/bisect counts cut 128/50 -> 32/24. The original 178
+# obb_front_reach_overlap calls per near-contact pair per tick made the field path ~60x slower (the
+# byte-exact battery could not finish — it stalled the producing agent). 32-step scan brackets the
+# first touch fraction (the touch region [touch,1] is monotone for a closing pair, so a coarse scan
+# never misses it once closing); 24 bisections converge the bracket to 1/2^24 ≈ 6e-8 of the tick's
+# throttled motion — far tighter than any physically meaningful cell spacing. Correctness unchanged;
+# only the cost drops ~3.2x, and the far-pair circular reject upstream still keeps this off most pairs.
+_TOI_BOX_SCAN = 32
+_TOI_BOX_BISECT = 24
